Endangerment Degree

Vulnerable: most children speak the language, but it may be restricted to certain domains (e.g., home) Definitely endangered: children no longer learn the language as a mother tongue in the home Severely endangered: language is spoken by grandparents and older generations; while the parent generation may understand it, they do not speak it to children or among themselves Critically endangered: the youngest speakers are grandparents and older, and they speak the language partially and infrequently Extinct: there are no speakers left

Find out how many speakers exists under each degree, obviously extinct wont have any speakers at all.

lang_data %>% group_by(endangerment_degree)%>% arrange(desc(Number_of_speakers))%>%  ggplot(aes(x=factor(endangerment_degree),y=Number_of_speakers,fill=factor(endangerment_degree                                                                           )))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+theme(legend.position = "None",axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90,hjust=0.4))+labs(x="Endangerment Degree",y="No of Speakers")+scale_fill_manual(values=c("brown4","darkgoldenrod3","darkgrey","mediumvioletred","darkolivegreen4"))

## Languages under Extinct degree Which country has got more extinct languages

lang_data %>% filter(endangerment_degree=="Extinct")%>%group_by(country)%>% summarize(n=n())%>%arrange(desc(n))%>%ggplot(aes(x=factor(country,levels=country),y=n))+geom_bar(stat="identity",width=0.4,color="chartreuse4")+coord_flip()+labs(x="Country",y="No of Languages",title="Countrywise Extinct Languages")

Find out the number of languages under endangerment degree, around 250 languages are under Extinct category, for which measures should be taken to preseve it.

degree_data<-lang_data %>% group_by(endangerment_degree) %>% summarise(lang_count=n_distinct(name_english),speakers=sum(Number_of_speakers))%>% arrange(desc(speakers))


ggplot(degree_data,aes(x=endangerment_degree,y=lang_count,fill=endangerment_degree))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+scale_fill_manual(values=c("brown4","darkgoldenrod3","darkgrey","mediumvioletred","darkolivegreen4"))+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))+labs(x="Endangerment Degree",y="Language Count")

ggplot(degree_data,aes(x=endangerment_degree,y=lang_count,col=speakers))+geom_point(size=5)+
  xlab("Degree of endangerment") + ylab("Languages") +
 ggtitle("Degree of endangerment vs speakers")

Find out which country has most languages, USA was top1, which has got more than 280 languages.

patt<- ANY_CHAR %R% ANY_CHAR %R% ANY_CHAR
code<-unique(str_extract(lang_data$country_code,patt))
l2<-lang_data[lang_data$country_code %in% code,]
l2 %>% select(name_english,country_code)%>% group_by(country_code)%>%summarise(n=n())%>% arrange(desc(n))%>%head(20)%>%ggplot(aes(x=factor(country_code),y=n))+geom_area(stat="identity",alpha=0.5,color="mediumvioletred",size=4)+geom_point(color="black",size=3)+theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))+labs(x="country code",y="Language Count",title="Countries Language Count - Top 20")

Mapping extinct languages

elang<-lang_data%>%filter(endangerment_degree=="Extinct")
lon<-elang$longitude
lat<-elang$latitude
library(maps)
## Warning: package 'maps' was built under R version 3.3.2
map("world", fill=TRUE, col="lightgreen", bg="lightblue", ylim=c(-60, 90), mar=c(0,0,0,0))

points(lon,lat, col="orange4", pch=16)

#cols<-brewer.pal(n=5,name="Set1")
cols<-c("brown4","darkgoldenrod3","blue","mediumvioletred","darkolivegreen4")
cols_m1<-cols[factor(lang_data$endangerment_degree)]
map("world", fill=TRUE, col="lightgrey", bg="lightblue", ylim=c(-60, 90), mar=c(0,0,0,0))

points(lang_data$longitude,lang_data$latitude, col=cols_m1, pch=16)
legend(x=-50,y=-30,legend=paste(rep(c("Definitely Endangered","Critically Endangered","Extinct","Severely Endangered","Vulnerable"),times=1)),
                             col=rep(cols,times=1),pch=16,bty="0",cex=0.5,pt.cex=0.7)
